doc.ContractDescription: PRUNING THE TREE OF LIFE: EVOLUTION AND ECOLOGY IN RESPONSE TO THE LATE ORDOVICIAN MASS EXTINCTION. THE PROPOSAL WILL FOCUS ON THE CHANGES THAT OCCUR TO BOTH EVOLUTIONARY PATTERNS AND ECOLOGICAL PROCESSES AS A RESULT OF THE LATE ORDOVICIAN MASS EXTINCTION. MASS EXTINCTIONS CAN PLAY A KEY ROLE IN SHAPING THE HISTORY OF ADVANCED LIFE ON EARTH, BUT FOR SOME EXTINCTIONS THE EFFECTS CAN BE RELATIVELY MUTED. THE REASONS FOR THIS VARIATION REMAIN UNCERTAIN, HINDERING OUR UNDERSTANDING OF THE ROLE OF MASS EXTINCTIONS IN THE EVOLUTION OF ADVANCED LIFE. MOST STUDIES OF EXTINCTION AND RECOVERY HAVE FOCUSED ON COUNTS OF SPECIES OR HIGHER TAXA EITHER GLOBALLY OR WITHIN REGIONS. HOWEVER, THIS ACCOUNTING OF DIVERSITY IGNORES THE IMPORTANT ROLE THAT EVOLUTIONARY HISTORY HAS PLAYED IN ESTABLISHING EVOLUTIONARY RATES WITHIN CLADES AND PREDICTING LOCAL AND REGIONAL COMMUNITY STRUCTURES. WE PROPOSE TO INVESTIGATE THE LATE ORDOVICIAN MASS EXTINCTION AND RECOVERY WITH PHYLOGENETIC METHODS THAT QUANTIFY EVOLUTIONARY HISTORY. MODERN ECOLOGISTS AND CONSERVATION BIOLOGISTS, FACED WITH PRESERVING MODERN BIODIVERSITY THROUGH A POTENTIAL MASS EXTINCTION, HAVE DEVELOPED METHODS TO QUANTIFY THE LOSS OF EVOLUTIONARY HISTORY BASED ON PHYLOGENIES OF LIVING ORGANISMS. WE WILL DEVELOP PHYLOGENIES FOR TWO IMPORTANT GROUPS OF MARINE TAXA IN THE ORDOVICIAN AND SILURIAN, STROPHOMENID AND ORTHID BRACHIOPODS, AND USE THESE PHYLOGENIES TO ANALYZE BOTH THE DYNAMICS OF EVOLUTION AND THE ESTABLISHMENT OF ECOLOGICAL COMMUNITIES BEFORE AND AFTER THE EXTINCTION. TO OUR KNOWLEDGE, OUR PROPOSED PROJECT WOULD BE THE FIRST APPLICATION FOR MANY OF THESE PHYLOGENETIC METHODS TO THE STUDY OF MASS EXTINCTIONS. WE CHOOSE THE LATE ORDOVICIAN MASS EXTINCTION FOR OUR STUDY BECAUSE A) THE ORDOVICIAN AND SILURIAN HAVE A WELL-KNOWN FOSSIL RECORD FROM MULTIPLE PALEOCONTINENTS, ALLOWING FOR THE INVESTIGATION OF THE IMPRINT OF THE MASS EXTINCTION ON ECOLOGICAL AND EVOLUTIONARY HISTORY AT MULTIPLE SPATIAL AND TEMPORAL SCALES; B) THE MASS EXTINCTION IS LIKELY THE RESULT OF SEVERE CLIMATIC FLUCTUATIONS AND GLACIAL EXPANSION, MAKING IT A GOOD CONTRAST TO THE EXTRATERRESTRIALLY DRIVEN EXTINCTION AT THE END OF THE CRETACEOUS, AND C) THE ECOLOGICAL AND EVOLUTIONARY EFFECTS ARE THOUGHT TO BE MORE MODERATE THAN FOR OTHER EXTINCTIONS, MAKING IT AN IMPORTANT COUNTERPOINT TO LATER EXTINCTIONS.
